<doc id="82664" url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=82664" title="Ascalaphus">
Ascalaphus

The name Ascalaphus (, "Askalaphos") is shared by two people in Greek mythology.
Son of Acheron and Orphne.
Ascalaphus was the custodian of the orchard of Hades. He told the other gods that Persephone had eaten pomegranate seeds in the Underworld. Because she had tasted food in the underworld, Persephone was obliged to return to the Underworld and spend four months (in later versions six months) there every year.
Demeter was so angry because of this and she buried him beneath a heavy rock in the Underworld. When Heracles went to the underworld, he rolled the stone away and released Ascalaphus from his prison but then Demeter transformed Ascalaphus into a screech owl. According to another myth Persephone herself changed him into an owl by sprinkling him with water of the river Phlegethon. As a screech owl, he became the familiar bird of Hades, god of the underworld.
Son of Ares and Astyoche.
Ascalaphus was King of Orchomenus, and twin brother of Ialmenus. He and his twin were counted among the Argonauts and the suitors of Helen, and led the Orchomenian contingent in the Trojan War, where a spear thrown by Deiphobus killed him.

</doc>
<doc id="82665" url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=82665" title="Orphne">
Orphne

In Greek mythology, Orphne (, from , "darkness"), also known as Styx (Στύξ) or Gorgyra (, from , "underground drain"), was a nymph that lived in Hades. With Acheron, she mothered Ascalaphus.
Orphne also seems to be one translation of the name of the Roman goddess Caligo (Darkness).

</doc>
<doc id="82666" url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=82666" title="2002 US Open (tennis)">
2002 US Open (tennis)

The 2002 US Open was held between August 26 – September 8, 2002.
Both Lleyton Hewitt and Venus Williams were unsuccessful in their title defences, Hewitt being defeated in the semifinals by Andre Agassi and Venus being defeated in the final by her younger sister Serena in the final. It was the third of four consecutive Grand Slam titles won by Serena, all won by defeating Venus in the final. Pete Sampras, runner-up in 2001, won his fifth US Open title, and his 14th and final Grand Slam title, defeating his rival Agassi in the final in four sets.

